DATA CLOUD
View Your Data in Data Explorer

In Data Explorer, you can view selected Data Cloud data from your data lake objects (DLOs), data models objects (DMOs), calculated insight objects (CIOs), or data graphs. You can personalize your view by editing the columns and use filters to show only the most relevant data for the selected object.

REQUIRED EDITIONS
Available in: Lightning Experience

If you don’t see Data Explorer, contact your admin to enable Data Explorer permissions.

NOTE We recommend referring Data Cloud Glossary of Terms to get familiar with the definition of terms associated with Data Cloud.

To view your data, select an object type. The maximum display is 100 rows.

Clicking a data column sorts the data based on that selection.

NOTE The dates and times displayed in Data Explorer are based on the time zone configured in your system. When ingested date value in a column is 01/01/0001, it's rendered as 01/01/1901.
Copy SOQL

Use Copy SOQL, to execute SOQL to return a similar result set. This data includes the query that’s running to populate the table. This function copies only the SOQL generated for the table that you’re viewing. If a table has more than 10 columns, Data Cloud copies only the SOQL for the 10 columns showing.

Data Explorer retrieves up to 100 records of DMOs or DLOs per query. If you want to run a query to retrieve all records, click Copy SOQL, copy the query, remove the 'LIMIT 100' condition, and execute it via Developer Console.

Calculated Insights Chart View

After choosing a CIO, view your calculated insight objects in Chart view by selecting the pie icon.

This view lets you view your CIOs in a graph to visualize and further analyze your data.

NOTE Boolean fields store two possible values, ‘true’ or ‘false’. If a selected boolean field has null or empty values, it always defaults to ‘false’.
Data Graph Records

To view a data graph's records, select Data Graphs as the object type, then select the data graph.

To view a data graph record's data, click the record's View link. To copy a data graph record's data, click the record's Copy link.
